<li id="cite_note-understandingtaxes-7">^ <a href="#cite_ref-understandingtaxes_7-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-understandingtaxes_7-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://web.archive.org/web/20070816190910/http://www.irs.gov/app/understandingTaxes/jsp/whys/lp/IWT5L1lp.jsp" class="external text" title="http://web.archive.org/web/20070816190910/http://www.irs.gov/app/understandingTaxes/jsp/whys/lp/IWT5L1lp.jsp" rel="nofollow">Internal Revenue Service</a>: The luxury tax is a progressive tax--it takes more from the wealthy than from the poor.</li>
<li id="cite_note-luxury-8">^ <a href="#cite_ref-luxury_8-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-luxury_8-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="http://concise.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370763/luxury-tax" class="external text" title="http://concise.britannica.com/ebc/article-9370763/luxury-tax" rel="nofollow">Luxury tax - Britannica Online Encyclopedia</a>: Excise levy on goods or services considered to be luxuries rather than necessities. Modern examples are taxes on jewelry and perfume. Luxury taxes may be levied with the intent of taxing the rich...</li>
